          <avActivityHighlights>More moist snow slides and avalanches are possible.</avActivityHighlights>
          <avActivityComment>The surface of the snowpack has frozen to form a strong crust and will soften during the day. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; In particular on very steep slopes and in steep rocky terrain more small and, in isolated cases, medium-sized moist snow slides and avalanches are possible as the penetration by moisture increases.</avActivityComment>
          <snowpackStructureComment>The surface of the snowpack has frozen to form a strong crust and will already soften in the late morning. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; Below approximately 2500 m: The snowpack is moist and its surface has a melt-freeze crust. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; Below approximately 2400 m only a little snow is lying on south facing slopes. Above approximately 1600 m there is still a very large amount of snow on north facing slopes.</snowpackStructureComment>
        </BulletinMeasurements>
